Despite the economic downtrn due to the COVID-19 pandemic, Nigeria has been able to improve its income through the Value Added Tax (VAT) as the sum of N651.77 billion was generated in the first six months of the year. According to data in the sectoral distribution of VAT data for first half of 2020 released by the National Bureau of Statistics (NBS) yesterday, the sum of N651.77 billion generated as VAT in H1 2020 represents 8.45 per cent growth year-on-year as against N600.98 billion generated in H1 2019. With the implementation of the 2020 Finance Act, VAT in Nigeria had been increased to 7.5 per cent from 5 per cent which it had been, effective February this year. At 7.5 per cent, VAT in Nigeria is still among the lowest amongst its peers across the world. Data released by NBS show that professional services generated the highest amount of VAT with N75.92 billion and closely followed by the manufacturing sector which generated N67.63 billion, commercial and trading sector generated N31.10 billion. Mining generated the least closely followed by textile and garment industry and pharmaceutical, soaps and toiletries with N127.58 million, N499.19 million and N648.78 million generated respectively. Out of the total amount generated in first half of 2020, N335.82 billion was generated as non-import VAT locally while N161.74 billion was generated as non-import VAT for foreign. The balance of N154.21 billion was generated as NCS-Import VAT. When compared to what was generated in the various sectors in the first three months of the year, income generated from VAT dropped in the second quarter for most sectors but overall increased slightly by 0.81 per cent. Total VAT in Q2 2020 stood at N327.195 billion compared to N324.579 billion in Q1 2020. Transport and haulage services saw a 64.84 per cent increase in VAT collection in the second quarter of the year followed by local government councils which had 51.5 per cent increase. N12.63 billion and N483.349 million had been collected in the transport and haulage services sector and local government councils in Q2 compared with N7.665 billion and N319.039 million collected in Q1 respectively. Increased VAT income was also recorded in the conglomerates sector in Q2 as N1.418 billion was generated compared to N1.104 billion generated in the first three months of the year reflecting a 28.4 per cent improvement. Total VAT revenue generated from the sector in the first six months of the year totalled N2.522 billion. However, the impact of the lockdown and COVID-19 pandemic reflected in the revenue generated from some sectors such as the hospitality, building and publishing sectors.  VAT generated from the hotels and catering sector dropped the most in the second quarter of the year, declining by 45.77 per cent to N1.367 billion from N2.521 billion. Publishing, printing and paper packaging saw a 40.04 per cent decline in VAT revenue which dropped to N331.47 million from N552.86 million while automobiles and assemblies and the petro-chemical and petroleum refineries sectors saw a 29.97 per cent drop in VAT revenue. The building and construction had also seen a 32 per cent decline in VAT revenue collected.